Sg68IX32EME5umKX17TAKVaahRWWo_xVQIiQ9Xdf32y7ev63NrW3_GRnmaSn4bRYEgCzDVwenGOcxqkVDmfKLw-QS35b0NSiFDHJfwZwXxnCxxdDe2oMPCdvIla1j7B56yRLLYH_J-HKv5P1ikEZ_rV9JDOsHtDQ6SVHsmGXbZwqTc5yUDfIjQooHvNtvI7vAKcOEHTgnO-iASB1vOc3ocAVRexoar-LkyMzf-k5e90MpJD_FIPEGb1aR4bB-0WLuB9SpWEctR78TfqDSjyneEQ==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering classloader coverage**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out why our legacy custom classloader isn't counting coverage—it seems like JaCoCo's dynamic access instrumentation only works for originally loaded classes. It might be that it loads a copy that isn't instrumented, which could cause coverage issues. I need to cover version 1 in the actual ZeroConfSupport class. To do that, maybe I’ll have to adjust the test stubs. We really shouldn't modify private fields directly using reflection, as it's better to stick to the public API.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test coverage strategy**\\n\\nI’m considering whether to change the stubs to v1 only, which might let me cover all three uncovered parts but could cause me to lose coverage for v3. I need to think about maintaining all coverage if possible. I wonder if I can create a separate source set, but that doesn’t seem feasible. Instead, I’ll look to use the javax.jmdns.JmDNS without the create method, focusing on testing the actual ZeroConfSupport class to ensure I capture the remaining pieces. It’s a bit complex, but I’ll aim for clarity!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing class coverage issues**\\n\\nI’m considering the implications of potentially removing v3 coverage—it seems like it could lead to problems. I need to ensure both versions are covered in the original class, but how can I toggle static fields without using reflection? I'm starting to question if class initialization happens only once. Can I instantiate the original class through the classloader? It seems coverage instruments known class names, but the dynamic access didn’t account for v1. I wonder if unsupported features are affecting my legacy tests.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test stubbing strategies**\\n\\nMaybe I should start with v1 stubs and generate v3 within the test using a custom classloader. The report shows that previous attempts used stubs, so if I switch to using v1, the remaining covered sites should work, but v3 sites would become uncovered. This might mean the system accumulates coverage across attempts, indicating progress. I should consider adding a test that runs a child Java process while addressing the context classloader. It's a bit tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading options**\\n\\nIt seems creating a new original class in the same loader might be impossible. I need to understand what the dynamic-access coverage collects; it instruments bytecode at runtime, possibly using ByteBuddy or ASM during class loading. My custom classloader reads the uninstrumented class, so could we get the instrumented version from the parent resource? No, that's not viable. Alternatively, I could load ZeroConfSupport using a URLClassLoader directly from the actual JAR file. That might work better!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Understanding Java Class Constructs**\\n\\nI'm thinking about static nested public classes and their defaults. I need to define a public no-argument constructor clearly. ServiceInfoClass needs a specific public constructor that takes `(String, String, int, int, int, Hashtable)`. So, it looks like the nested public static final class supports this requirement with the correct public constructor. That sounds good! I feel like I'm on the right track with these Java constructs!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_QtAiO6Hc2RbXSGG18NgytfAm|fc_026dd3de8ca7d1aa0169fb95dbb960819db8985c92128810f0", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/ch.qos.reload4j/reload4j/1.2.19/src/test/java/ch_qos_reload4j/reload4j/ZeroConfSupportTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage ch_qos_reload4j.reload4j;\n\nimport java.lang.reflect.Field;\nimport java.lang.reflect.Method;\nimport java.util.HashMap;\nimport java.util.Hashtable;\nimport java.util.Map;\n\nimport javax.jmdns.JmDNS;\nimport javax.jmdns.ServiceInfo;\n\nimport org.apache.log4j.net.ZeroConfSupport;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\n\npublic class ZeroConfSupportTest {\n    @Test\n    void constructsAdvertisesAndUnadvertisesUsingJmDns3Api() {\n        Map properties = new HashMap();\n        properties.put(\"application\", \"reload4j-test\");\n\n        ZeroConfSupport zeroConfSupport = new ZeroConfSupport(\"_log4j._tcp.local.\", 4560, \"reload4j\", properties);\n        Object jmDNSInstance = ZeroConfSupport.getJMDNSInstance();\n\n        assertThat(jmDNSInstance).isInstanceOf(JmDNS.class);\n        JmDNS jmDNS = (JmDNS) jmDNSInstance;\n\n        zeroConfSupport.advertise();\n\n        ServiceInfo registeredService = jmDNS.getRegisteredService();\n        assertThat(registeredService).isNotNull();\n        assertThat(registeredService.getType()).isEqualTo(\"_log4j._tcp.local.\");\n        assertThat(registeredService.getName()).isEqualTo(\"reload4j\");\n        assertThat(registeredService.getPort()).isEqualTo(4560);\n        assertThat(registeredService.getProperties()).containsEntry(\"application\", \"reload4j-test\");\n\n        zeroConfSupport.unadvertise();\n\n        assertThat(jmDNS.getRegisteredService()).isNull();\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void constructsAdvertisesAndUnadvertisesUsingLegacyJmDns1Api() throws Exception {\n        Field jmDNSClassField = getZeroConfSupportField(\"jmDNSClass\");\n        Field serviceInfoClassField = getZeroConfSupportField(\"serviceInfoClass\");\n   